{{More citations needed|date=May 2011}} {{Infobox magazine | title = Talk | logo = | logo_size = <!-- default is 180px --> | image_file = <!-- cover.jpg (omit the "file:" prefix) --> | image_size = <!-- default is 180px --> | image_alt = | image_caption = | editor = [[Tina Brown]] | editor_title = <!-- up to |editor_title5= --> | previous_editor = | staff_writer = | photographer = | category = | frequency = | format = | circulation = | publisher = | paid_circulation = | unpaid_circulation = | circulation_year = 2002 | total_circulation =670,000 | founder = Tina Brown<ref name="alger"/> | founded = {{Start date and age|1999|2}} | firstdate = {{Start date and age|1999|8|2}} | finaldate = {{End date|2002}} | finalnumber = | company = {{ubl|Talk Media|([[Miramax]])|[[Hearst Communications|Hearst Magazines]]|(Hearst)}} | country = [[United States]] | based = | language = English | website = talkmagazine.com (defunct) | issn = | oclc = }} '''''Talk''''' was an [[United States|American]] [[magazine]] published from 1999 to 2002. The magazine gained notoriety for its celebrity profiles and interviews.<ref name="alger"/> The magazine was a joint venture of [[Miramax]]'s Talk Media and [[Hearst Communications|Hearst Magazines]]. Hearst would manage circulation, manufacturing, newsstand distribution and subscription fulfillment. Talk Media was in charge of advertising sales, editorial content and marketing.<ref name=hearst/>
==History and profile== Talk Media was founded in July 1998 by [[Miramax|Miramax Films]], [[Tina Brown]] and Ron Galotti to publishing books and Talk magazine and produce television programs. Talk Media formed a joint venture with [[Hearst Communications|Hearst Magazines]] for the magazine only in February 1999.<ref name=hearst>{{cite news|title=Miramax Films and Hearst Magazines Announce Plans to Publish Talk|url=http://www.hearst.com/newsroom/miramax-films-and-hearst-magazines-announce-plans-to-publish-talk|accessdate=February 16, 2016|work=Hearst Publishing|date=February 11, 1999}}</ref>
The first issue of ''Talk'' appeared in September 1999.<ref name="alger">{{cite news|author1=Alex Kuczynski|author2=Geraldine Fabrikant|title=Lifelines Cut, Talk Magazine Goes Silent|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/01/19/business/lifelines-cut-talk-magazine-goes-silent.html|accessdate=16 February 2016|work=The New York Times|date=19 January 2002}}</ref> The cover story of the debut issue was an interview with [[Hillary Clinton]], which took place shortly after the [[Clinton-Lewinsky scandal]], in which she explained that her husband [[Bill Clinton]] had a chronic need to please women. ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported that at times, "''Talk'' seemed more interested in promoting such Miramax stars as [[Gwyneth Paltrow]] than in politics."<ref>{{cite news|last=Kurtz |first=Howard |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/2002/01/19/tina-browns-talk-magazine-suddenly-silenced/1871c9ba-e75e-46ee-9af2-f975e32f0180/ |title=Tina Brown's Talk Magazine Suddenly Silenced |publisher=The Washington Post |date=2002-01-19 |accessdate=2017-05-05}}</ref> However, the magazine never became a commercial success, and was shut down<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/03/business/media/03carr.html?hp|title=The Media Equation; 10 Years Ago, An Omen No One Saw|author=David Carr|date=3 August 2009|work=The New York Times|page=1|accessdate=6 May 2011}}</ref> on January 18, 2002.<ref name="alger"/> [[Politico.com]] estimated that Brown had "bombed through some $50 million in 2 1/2 years" on the failed venture. A $1 million contract settlement in 2002 ended Brown's involvement in Talk Media.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Norris |first=John |url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2014/05/tina-brown-how-to-lose-100-million-105907 |title=How to Lose $100 Million |work=POLITICO Magazine |publisher=Politico.com |date=May–June 2014 |accessdate=2017-05-05}}</ref>
